UART

Universal Asynchronous Receiver / Transmitter.

The "uart" component transmits and receives bytes over a serial connection.

UART is commonly used to:

• connect CPUs to terminals
• communicate between boards
• send debug messages
• implement simple serial protocols

The component handles:

• transmission timing
• reception timing
• busy state
• byte buffering

Internally, UART transmits frames according to a protocol definition.

There is no dedicated panel UI in v1. UART is typically used together with "terminal", "fifo", "protocol", or a teaching CPU.

───

Syntax

comp [uart] .name:
baud: 9600
protocol: .uart8n1
:

───

Attributes

Attribute| Type| Default| Description
baud| int| 9600| Transmission speed in bits per second
protocol| inline [protocol]| required| Frame format used by this UART

───

Baud

Baud specifies how many bits are transmitted per second.

Example:

baud: 9600

means:

9600 bits/second

Changing baud changes transmission speed but does not change the transmitted data.

───

Protocol

UART uses an "inline [protocol]" definition to describe the serial frame format.

Example:

inline [protocol] .uart8n1:

tx:
0
data 8b
1

:

Meaning:

start bit
8 data bits
stop bit

This is a simplified UART 8N1 frame.

───

Inputs

send

Transmit one value.

.uart:{
send = value
set = signal
}

When:

signal

transitions:

0 -> 1

the value is queued for transmission.

───

rx

Serial receive line.

.uart:rx = wire

Usually connected to another UART's "tx".

───

Outputs

tx

Serial transmit line.

1wire tx =
.uart:tx

Provides the serial bit stream generated from the selected protocol.

───

data

Last received value.

8wire data =
.uart:data

───

dataReady

Reception event.

1bit ready =
.uart:dataReady

Transitions:

0 -> 1

when a complete frame has been received and decoded.

───

busy

Transmission status.

1bit busy =
.uart:busy

Returns:

1

while UART is transmitting.

Returns:

0

when idle.

