───

Runnable — UART with FIFO

Transmit queue:

comp [fifo] .tx:
width: 8
length: 64
:

UART:

comp [uart] .uart0:
baud: 9600
protocol: .uart8n1
:

Producer:

.tx:{
push = acc
set = printInstruction
}

Consumer:

.uart0:{
send = .tx:front
set = txNext
}

.tx:{
pop = 1
set = txNext
}

FIFO stores bytes while UART is busy.

───

Runnable — CPU debug output

comp [uart] .debug:
baud: 9600
protocol: .uart8n1
:

comp [terminal] .console:
rows: 20
columns: 80
:

CPU:

.debug:{
send = acc
set = print
}

Display:

.console:{
append = .debug:data
set = .debug:dataReady
}

Whenever the CPU executes a print instruction, the accumulator value is transmitted and displayed.

───

Relationship to Protocol

"inline [protocol]" defines:

value
↓
frame bits

Example:

data = ^41

↓

0 01000001 1

───

"comp [uart]" defines:

frame bits
↓
time

according to:

baud

Therefore:

• "protocol" describes the frame format
• "uart" describes transmission over time

───

Common Errors

Error| Cause
protocol is required| Missing protocol definition
Unknown protocol instance| Invalid protocol reference
UART receive width mismatch| RX frame incompatible with protocol
send value width mismatch| Value cannot be encoded by protocol
baud must be greater than 0| Invalid baud value

───

Notes

UART does not define the frame format itself.

Frame structure is always provided by an "inline [protocol]" instance.

This allows custom UART variants to be implemented without changing the UART component.

Examples:

.uart8n1
.uart7e1
.uartCustom

all use the same UART component while transmitting different frame layouts.


